) {\n   287→      const p = popcount(leftMasksLow[k] & lBig) & 1;\n   288→      const val = constants[k] ^ p;\n   289→      if (val) partial |= 1n << BigInt(k);\n   290→    }\n   291→    leftPartials[lA] = partial;\n   292→  }\n   293→\n   294→  // For each right assignment, compute right parity vector\n   295→  // Then for each left partial, full = partial XOR rightParity, weight = popcount(full)\n   296→  // We want minimum weight, then best tie-breaker.\n   297→\n   298→  // To make this efficient: for each right assignment, compute rightParity.\n   299→  // Then iterate over all left partials and compute full = partial XOR rightParity.\n   300→  // This is O(leftCount * rightCount * popcount_time).\n   301→\n   302→  // With halfL=20 and halfR=20: 1M * 1M = 1T - too slow!\n   303→  // We need to be smarter.\n   304→\n   305→  // Group left partials by value, then for each right parity vector, find the\n   306→  // left partial that when XORed with right gives minimum popcount.\n   307→  // This is finding nearest neighbor in Hamming space.\n   308→\n   309→  // For numVars up to 40, the partial vectors are 40-bit numbers.\n   310→  // We can group left partials into buckets by their value and for each right vector,\n   311→  // check all left partials at increasing Hamming distances.\n   312→\n   313→  // Alternative: since we need minimum weight, and the search space is 2^40,\n   314→  // let's try a different strategy. For each desired weight w (starting from 0),\n   315→  // check if any solution of weight w exists. The first w that works gives us our answer.\n   316→\n   317→  // Actually, let's use a smarter approach: sort leftPartials, then for each rightParity,\n   318→  // the full = leftPartial XOR rightParity, we want minimum popcount.\n   319→  // popcount(full) = popcount(leftPartial XOR rightParity).\n   320→  // So we want the leftPartial closest (in Hamming distance) to rightParity.\n   321→  // This is the nearest neighbor search problem. With 1M