ion almost certainly has very few buttons pressed. We can search by weight:\n\nFor weight w = 0: check if the zero vector is a solution (all buttons unpressed).\nFor weight w = 1: check each of the 40 buttons individually.\nFor weight w = 2: check all C(40,2) = 780 pairs.\nFor weight w = 3: check all C(40,3) = 9880 triples.\n...\n\nThis approach is O(C(n,w) * numLights) per weight level. For small w (which is the common case), this is very fast.\n\nFor the toggle problem: we check if pressing a specific subset of buttons achieves the target. Pressing buttons S means toggling the lights that each button affects. The resulting state is the XOR of the button vectors for all buttons in S.\n\nWe can compute this as: for each light, count how many buttons in S toggle it. If count is odd, the light is on.\n\nSo for weight w, we enumerate all C(numButtons, w) subsets. For each, compute the resulting light state and compare to target.\n\nFor w = 1: 40 checks.\nFor w = 2: 780 checks.  \nFor w = 3: 9880 checks.\nFor w = 40: 1 check.\nTotal across all w up to 40: sum of C(40,w) for w=0..40 = 2^40 ≈ 1 trillion. Too slow.\n\nBut we don't need to go up to w=40. The answer will typically have small weight. If we can determine the minimum weight from the Gaussian elimination, we only need to search at that weight.\n\nActually, here's a better idea: after Gaussian elimination, we know the solution space is an affine subspace. The minimum weight of any element in this subspace is what we need. We can compute a particular solution and the null space basis vectors.\n\nFor GF(2): let x0 be the particular solution (all free vars = 0). The null space is spanned by vectors n_1, ..., n_k (one per free variable). The solution space is {x0 + sum_j(c_j * n_j) : c_j in {0,1}}.\n\nThe weight of x0 + sum(c_j * n_j) is the Hamming weight of the XOR. To find minimum weight, we need the nearest codeword problem.\n\nFor the specific case of many identical buttons: x0 = [1,0,0,...,0] (only button 0 pre